// DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH ONLY. The real fix for the IAP plugin's release crash
// (__swift_instantiateConcreteTypeFromMangledName, Swift SR-11564) lives
// in the Swift source: IapPlugin now resolves CONCRETE Encodable structs,
// which take Tauri's `resolve<T: Encodable>` overload (straight
// JSONEncoder, no reflection) instead of `resolve(JsonObject)` →
// `JsonValue.prepare()`, whose `value as? [String: Any?]` dynamic cast was
// the actual trap. See the header comment in ios/Sources/IapPlugin.swift.
//
// This file stays because Tauri's `invoke.reject(...)` STILL routes through
// `prepare()` (we can't change Tauri's method), and so do any other
// plugins' dict-based resolves. Pointing XCODE_XCCONFIG_FILE here (CI:
// .github/workflows/ios.yml) applies these to EVERY target — including
// SwiftPM dependency targets a .pbxproj edit can't reach:
//   -Onone               → compiler emits direct type refs, not lazy
//                          mangled-name instantiations
//   DEAD_CODE_STRIPPING=NO → keep the type metadata at link time
// Slower/larger, but this is an observation-only companion app where
// correctness >> a few hundred KB. NOTE: this alone did NOT fix v0.2.14 —
// it may not propagate to SwiftPM targets under Tauri's xcodebuild — which
// is exactly why the v0.2.15 source-level Encodable fix was needed.
SWIFT_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL = -Onone
DEAD_CODE_STRIPPING = NO
